<turn speaker="Lyn_Vaughn" spkrtype="female" startTime="562.613" endTime="574.278">
 Most scientists say childhood is the best time to learn a second language. Researchers wanted to know why, so they watched the brain in action. Ann Kellan reports, the differences between young and old are dramatic.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Myla_Ryava" spkrtype="child" startTime="574.278" endTime="577.122">
 Can only be a hundred and forty
</turn>
<turn speaker="Ann_Kellan" spkrtype="female" startTime="577.122" endTime="583.408">
 Myla Ryava moved to the United States from Bulgaria when she was three.
<time sec="581.229"/>
 Learning English for her was a cinch.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Myla_Ryava" spkrtype="child" startTime="583.408" endTime="590.061">
 The answers could be fifty, the answer could be thirty and the answer could be forty.
<time sec="588.409"/>
 Take your best answer.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Ann_Kellan" spkrtype="female" startTime="590.061" endTime="592.263">
 Myla's parents are having a tougher time.
</turn>
<turn speaker="spkr_5" spkrtype="male" dialect="non-native" startTime="592.263" endTime="595.636">
 ea- It's h- hard to learn English after thirty years.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Ann_Kellan" spkrtype="female" startTime="595.636" endTime="632.501">
 Why is it generally more difficult for adults to learn a new language?
<time sec="599.260"/>
 Researchers at Sloan Kettering Cancer Center are starting to answer this question.
<time sec="603.321"/>
 Using a machine called a functional MRI, they monitor the brain activity of twelve volunteers who speak more than one language.
<time sec="610.776"/>
 Some learned a second language as children, while others learned in high school or college.
<time sec="615.410"/>
 [[NS]]
<time sec="616.947"/>
 Anne Merkich, a study volunteer learned to speak Croatian and English as a child.
<time sec="621.742"/>
 She helps demonstrate how the study was conducted. Once the MRI scanner is turned on, she will watch some slides and is told to think about the pictures.
<time sec="629.771"/>
 First in English, then in Croatian.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Anne_Merkich" spkrtype="female" startTime="632.501" endTime="637.250">
 I thought, oh, good morning, sun. You know, what a wonderful day we had ah- ahead of us.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Ann_Kellan" spkrtype="female" startTime="637.250" endTime="641.746">
 No matter what language Anne used, the same spot in her brain was active.
</turn>
<turn speaker="spkr_6" spkrtype="female" startTime="641.746" endTime="649.202">
 Yellow is Croatian, and red is English. And you see in this area, they're completely overlapping.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Ann_Kellan" spkrtype="female" startTime="649.202" endTime="658.948">
 That wasn't the case when people learned another language later in life.
<time sec="653.123"/>
 Those who learned a second language as teenagers use a separate area of the brain to process the new language.
</turn>
<turn speaker="spkr_7" spkrtype="female" startTime="658.948" endTime="666.260">
 It teaches us that the brain does different things
<time sec="662.357"/>
 with uh a late language as compared to an early language.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Ann_Kellan" spkrtype="female" startTime="666.260" endTime="673.549">
 The results of this study are already having an impact in the way brain surgeons perform, and, more importantly, prepare for surgery.
</turn>
<turn speaker="spkr_8" spkrtype="male" startTime="673.549" endTime="681.015">
 These are the areas of activation that are responsible for speech production. 
<time sec="677.817"/>
 This bright white area here is where the tumor is.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Ann_Kellan" spkrtype="female" startTime="681.015" endTime="686.399">
 Then brain surgeons try to avoid the language centers of the patient's brain when removing the tumor.
</turn>
<turn speaker="spkr_11" spkrtype="female" startTime="686.399" endTime="711.600">
 Do you think now is a good time for you to learn a language or do you think you should wait a little longer?
<time sec="690.443"/>
 [[NS]]
